en1 = "Welcome to Burmester. My name is X and I will be your guide for the next approximately 30 minutes. During our visit, we will talk about the history of Port Wine and its winemaking and aging process. At the end of the tour, we will proceed to the tasting."

en2 = """
Facing the photos:
Would you like to start the tour by telling me what comes to mind when you think of Port Wine? Is it different from table wine?

Port wine is a fortified wine, which makes it quite different from the more commonly found wines. To understand the matter well, let's talk about the differences in terms of sugar and alcohol content. Table wines are wines that mainly contain 12% to 14% alcohol, while Ports average about 20%. Regarding residual sugar, table wines typically have less than 10 grams per liter, contrasting with an average of 100 grams of sugar per liter for Ports. Being stronger and sweeter, Ports are usually enjoyed as an aperitif or with dessert.

Now that we can differentiate table wine, I will explain how Port wine became the fortified wine it is today, and how this intertwines with the history of the Burmester cellars. In 1750, two Englishmen, John Nash and Henry Burmester, founded the Burmester wine cellars here in Vila Nova de Gaia. At that time, Port wine was a table wine, like the Douro wines that still exist today. It was only in the 19th century that wines acquired the characteristics we now define as fortified, so I can safely say that Burmester participated in the transformation process of Port wine.

But what transformation was this? Imagine yourselves as Port wine merchants during the 18th century. Imagine the difficulties of transporting such merchandise at that time. To make the wine more durable, producers added strong brandy to the wine before transport. At some point lost in history, a group of producers began to add brandy during fermentation, and thus the wine became fortified. But what does fermentation have to do with wine transformation? To answer these questions, we must consider what happens during fermentation. Fermentation is the natural process of transforming sugars into alcohol, through the action of microorganisms called yeasts. By adding brandy, the yeasts are eliminated, resulting in the retention of sugar - hence the sweetness of the wine - and an increase in alcohol content.
"""

en3 = """Let's understand how the winemaking process works:
Harvest: Harvesting of the grapes usually takes place in September.
Transport to the winery: The grapes and the winery are located in the Douro Valley region, 120 meters up the Douro River. The wine is brought to Vila Nova de Gaia only for aging.
Destemming: Removal of the stems, part of the grapevine.
Treading: Traditionally, Port wine grapes were crushed by foot in stone lagares to extract the juice. Today, many wineries use mechanical presses to squeeze the grapes.
Maceration (Optional): In some cases, especially in the production of red wines and rosés, the berries may undergo a maceration period after destemming. During this period, the berries are left in contact with the skins to extract color, flavor, and tannins. For white wines, this step is often omitted, as the goal is to produce a clearer wine.
Pressing: After destemming and, if applicable, maceration, the berries are transferred to a press. There are various types of presses, from pneumatic presses to hydraulic presses, each with its specific characteristics. The press exerts pressure on the berries, squeezing out their juice.
Transfer: usually at this point, the wine is brought to Gaia.
Maturation: The wine can age in different containers. We will talk more about this stage in the next part of the tour. Before we proceed, I draw your attention to the historical cellars we have above us. There, we have Vintage wines, remember this name, as we will talk more about it later.
"""

en4 = """If we want a wine with grape characteristics such as taste, notes, and color, we usually age it in stainless steel tanks - more common with white wines. If we want something that retains fruit characteristics but gains woody notes, we leave it in large vats like these, which is more common among Rubies. Wines that undergo the most change during aging are those kept in small barrels. The smaller the barrel, the more contact with the wood and the more exposure to oxygen, as wood is porous.
"""

en5 = """Still talking about the aging of wines, it is important to note that white and red wines change color in opposite directions. Due to contact with wood and oxygen, white wines become darker over time, while red wines become lighter.

Another important point is the typology of Port wines. Wines are classified according to their colors. White wines are White, Ruby wines are made from red grapes with a color reminiscent of ruby ​​stone; Tawny wines are red wines that become more "tanned", which harks back to the etymology of the word: Tanné / Tanned.
Another classification is whether the wines are from a single year or a blend of years. Wines from a single year are allowed to be made when the harvest of the year is special and then aged. Single-year wines include Vintage (which ages in the bottle), LBV (from a special year, which cannot be bottled as vintage), and Colheita (Tawny aged in wooden barrels that acquire spicy notes).
"""

